    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, but the deadlock seems pretty random. it's not always the same resource. sometimes it's the inventory lock, sometimes it's something in the user session table. it almost feels like there's some unpredictable interference or just something \"glitchy\" happening in the background that we aren't seeing in the logs. \n\nany ideas why it would jump around like that instead of hitting a consistent bottleneck?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the elusive nature of your problem sounds like it's being caused by a \"glitchy\" background process, as you put it. In the world of server management, this could be due to a variety of factors. It might be that your server is running out of memory, causing it to swap to disk and slow down. It could also be that your server is running out of CPU resources, causing it to become unresponsive. Another possibility is that there's a bug in your code that's causing it to behave unpredictably under certain conditions. To get to the bottom of this, you'll need to do some thorough investigation. Start by monitoring your server's resource usage to see if there's a pattern to the deadlocks. You can also enable more detailed logging to see if you can identify any patterns in the errors. Finally, consider running a code review to see if there's any bug that could be causing the issue. Remember, in the world of server management, it's always better to be prepared for the unexpected than to be caught off guard by a deadlock.",
